Sure — here’s a simple, privacy‑safe JavaScript snippet that can read the embedded JSON data and generate a small **“Next Review Due”** badge on your crisis‑guide page. It uses only client‑side code and doesn’t send anything over the network.

```html
<script type="application/ld+json" id="guide-meta">
{
  "name": "Crisis & Aftercare Guide",
  "version": "1.0",
  "lastChecked": "2024-06-01",
  "reviewIntervalDays": 180,
  "checks": {
    "contrastCompliance": "WCAG AA or higher",
    "keyboardNavigation": true,
    "ariaRolesVerified": true,
    "resourceLinks": {
      "US": "https://988lifeline.org",
      "International": "https://findahelpline.com"
    },
    "ethicalBoundary": "maintain link to real human crisis support"
  },
  "contactForUpdates": "safety-admin@example.org"
}
</script>

<script>
(function () {
  try {
    const meta = JSON.parse(document.getElementById("guide-meta").textContent);
    const last = new Date(meta.lastChecked);
    const next = new Date(last.getTime() + meta.reviewIntervalDays * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000);
    const daysRemaining = Math.ceil((next - new Date()) / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24));

    const badge = document.createElement("div");
    badge.className = "review-badge";
    badge.textContent =
      daysRemaining > 0
        ? `Next review due in ${daysRemaining} days`
        : `🔶 Review overdue (${Math.abs(daysRemaining)} days ago)`;
    document.body.appendChild(badge);
  } catch (e) {
    console.error("Metadata parsing error:", e);
  }
})();
</script>

<style>
.review-badge {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0.5em;
  right: 0.5em;
  background: #0066cc;
  color: #fff;
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  padding: 0.4em 0.6em;
  border-radius: 4px;
  box-shadow: 0 0 3px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
  z-index: 1000;
}
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  .review-badge { background: #005eb8; color: #fff; }
}
@media print {
  .review-badge { display: none; }
}
</style>
```

**How it works**

- Reads the JSON block with the guide’s metadata.  
- Calculates the date when the next review is due.  
- Displays a small, color‑contrasted badge in the corner; it warns if overdue.  
- Adapts to dark mode and hides automatically when printed.

This lets anyone opening the page instantly see whether an accessibility or resource update is approaching, keeping the guide accurate and trustworthy.

